<p>
  A large PDF can be impossible to attach to an email, slow to upload to a web portal, and frustrating to share. This guide shows you how to compress a PDF and reduce its file size — for free, without installing software, and without sacrificing quality.
</p>

<h2>Why Are PDFs So Large?</h2>

<p>Before compressing, it helps to know what makes PDFs large:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>High-resolution images:</strong> A scanned document at 300+ DPI stores enormous amounts of image data. A single scanned A4 page can be 1–2 MB on its own.</li>
  <li><strong>Embedded fonts:</strong> PDFs embed complete font files so text looks identical on every device. Each embedded font adds 50–500 KB to the file size.</li>
  <li><strong>Redundant internal objects:</strong> Every time you edit and save a PDF in desktop software, new objects are added without removing the old ones. Over time, this "cruft" inflates the file significantly.</li>
  <li><strong>Unoptimised export settings:</strong> Exporting a document from Word, Excel, or PowerPoint with default settings often generates larger-than-necessary PDFs.</li>
</ul>

