<h2>Method 2: Compress a PDF on Windows (No Software)</h2>

<p>
  If you do not want to use an online tool, try these free Windows options:
</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Microsoft Word (if installed):</strong> Open the PDF in Word → Edit the document if needed → File → Export → Create PDF/XPS → click Options → tick "Minimum size (publishing online)." This significantly reduces size, especially for image-heavy PDFs.</li>
  <li><strong>Print to PDF:</strong> Open the PDF in Edge or Chrome → Ctrl+P → "Save as PDF" → Save. This re-renders the PDF and often produces a smaller file, though it may alter some formatting.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Method 3: Compress a PDF on Mac with Preview</h2>

<p>
  Mac's built-in Preview app has a built-in PDF compression filter:
</p>
<ol>
  <li>Open the PDF in <strong>Preview</strong>.</li>
  <li>Go to <strong>File → Export</strong> (not Save).</li>
  <li>Change the format to PDF.</li>
  <li>Click the <strong>Quartz Filter</strong> dropdown and select <strong>Reduce File Size</strong>.</li>
  <li>Click Save.</li>
</ol>
<p>
  Note: macOS's Reduce File Size filter can be aggressive with image quality reduction. Check the output before using it for print-quality documents.
</p>

<h2>Method 4: Compress PDF in Adobe Acrobat</h2>

<p>
  Adobe Acrobat Pro (paid) offers the most powerful compression options:
</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>File → Reduce File Size:</strong> Quick compression with adjustable PDF compatibility level.</li>
  <li><strong>File → Save as Other → Optimized PDF:</strong> Full control over image downsampling, font subsetting, and object removal. Offers the best compression ratios for complex PDFs.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Method 5: Compress PDF in Google Drive</h2>

<p>
  Google Drive does not compress PDFs directly, but there is a workaround:
</p>
<ol>
  <li>Upload the PDF to Google Drive.</li>
  <li>Right-click → <strong>Open with Google Docs</strong>.</li>
  <li>Go to <strong>File → Download → PDF</strong>.</li>
  <li>Google re-exports the PDF, often at a smaller size.</li>
</ol>
<p>
  Warning: this method converts the PDF through Google Docs, which can affect complex layouts and is not suitable for design documents.
</p>

<h2>How to Get the Best Compression Results</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>For text-heavy PDFs:</strong> Use our browser-based compressor — structural compression works best here.</li>
  <li><strong>For image-heavy or scanned PDFs:</strong> Reduce the images before embedding them. Convert each page to a lower-resolution JPG first (use our <a href="/pdfwonder/pdf-to-jpg">PDF to JPG tool</a>), then recombine with our <a href="/pdfwonder/jpg-to-pdf">Image to PDF converter</a> at a lower quality setting.</li>
  <li><strong>For repeatedly-edited PDFs:</strong> The "aggressive" option in our compressor removes metadata and unused objects accumulated through multiple edits, often giving the largest size reduction.</li>
  <li><strong>Remove unnecessary pages:</strong> Use the <a href="/pdfwonder/pdf-remove-pages">PDF Page Remover</a> to delete blank pages, cover pages, or appendices before compressing.</li>
</ul>

